<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="58" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1245,1701]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,1245,1270]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">Distribution.</emphasis>
Indo-Pacific from the Society Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Leis" box="[801,924,1245,1269]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" refString="Leis, J. M. (2006) Nomenclature and distribution of the species of the porcupinefish family Diodontidae (Pisces, Teleostei). Memoirs of the Museum of Victoria 63 (1), 77 - 90." type="journal article" year="2006">
Leis, 
<number box="[866,924,1245,1269]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) to the east coast of Africa from Algoa Bay, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,295,1281,1305]" name="South Africa" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(Leis in 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith" box="[399,683,1281,1305]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" refString="Smith, M. M. &amp; P. C. Heemstra (eds.) (1986) Smiths' Sea Fishes. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg, xx + 1047 pp." type="book" year="1986">
Smith &amp; Heemstra, 
<number box="[625,683,1281,1305]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="1986.0">1986</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) north to the Gulf of Aden (record based on 
<figureCitation box="[1192,1259,1281,1305]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,823,1689]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,823,1689]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 9. Diodon liturosus, Seven Brothers Islands, Gulf of Aden (J. E. Randall)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/202778/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[1245,1259,1281,1305]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
taken Rhounda Komaytu, Seven Brothers Islands) and the southern Red Sea from a video record (
<bibRefCitation author="Randall" box="[1089,1253,1317,1341]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" refString="Randall, J. E. (1994) Twenty-two new records of fishes from the Red Sea. Fauna of Saudi Arabia 14, 259 - 275." type="journal article" year="1994">
Randall, 
<number box="[1193,1253,1317,1341]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). We extend the range north in the Red Sea to Marsa Alam, 
<collectingCountry box="[639,706,1354,1378]" name="Egypt" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[721,803,1353,1377]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1178,1201]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,193,1156]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[139,1424,193,1157]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 10. Diodon liturosus, Marsa Shagra, Marsa Alam, Egypt (S. V. Bogorodsky)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/202779/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[774,803,1353,1377]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
) and to Ras Mohammed at the southern end of the Sinai Peninsula from observation in the Ras Mohammed National Park by Jean Michel Rose (pers. comm.) and Tania Malkerova kindly provided her underwater photo of 
<taxonomicName box="[740,927,1425,1449]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Diodontidae" genus="Diodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetraodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="liturosus">Diodon liturosus</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[943,1022,1425,1449]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1145,1168]" captionTargetBox="[186,1406,195,1130]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[186,1408,195,1130]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 11. Diodon liturosus, Dahab, Gulfof Aqaba (T. Malkerova)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/202780/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[995,1022,1425,1449]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
) taken at Dahab on the west coast of Sinai at 
<geoCoordinate box="[242,323,1461,1485]" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" precision="5555" value="28.5">
<number box="[242,292,1461,1485]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="28.5">28.5</number>
°N
</geoCoordinate>
that clearly shows small black spots on the fins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1245,1701]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,1497,1521]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">Remarks.</emphasis>
Two adult individuals were photographed by the first author in 
<quantity box="[1028,1113,1497,1521]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0952399999999995" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" unit="in" value="2006.0">2006 in</quantity>
Brayka Bay and Marsa Shagra in the Marsa Alam region of 
<collectingCountry box="[527,594,1534,1558]" name="Egypt" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(identification confirmed by Jeffrey M. Leis) at a depth of 
<quantity box="[1270,1342,1533,1557]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" unit="m" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2–5 m</quantity>
in coral reefs of a bay and a semi-enclosed deep lagoon; both fish were close to shelter, one near a large cave. They are unusual in having dark-spotted fins. 
<bibRefCitation author="Leis" box="[560,691,1605,1629]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" refString="Leis, J. M. (1977) Systematics and zoogeography of the porcupinefishes (Diodon, Diodontidae, Tetraodontiformes), with comments on egg and larval development. Fishery Bulletin 76 (3), 535 - 567." type="journal article" year="1977">
Leis (
<number box="[623,683,1605,1629]" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" value="1977.0">1977</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, in his review of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[998,1082,1605,1629]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Diodontidae" genus="Diodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetraodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[998,1082,1605,1629]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">Diodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described the fins of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Diodontidae" genus="Diodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetraodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="58" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="liturosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="58">D. liturosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as unmarked, except at the base, and he presently knows of no specimens or photographs extralimital to the Red Sea with dark spots on fins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
